1.2 Means and SEs (2 pts)

Figure 1 includes three distinct geometric representations:

  1. geom_point corresponding to the average stereotype score for each age group and gender.
  2. geom_line is used to connect the points across age groups.
  3. geom_errorbar corresponds to a range of +/- 1 standard error (SE) from the mean stereotype score for each age group and gender.

The next question asks you to create a plot similar to Figure 1. In order to do so, you will first need to calculate summary statistics for each of of several subgroups of observations. Calculate the mean, standard deviation, and sample size for each distinct subgroup represented in Figure 1. Then calculate the standard error for each subgroup using the formula: \[ SE = \frac{SD}{\sqrt{n}} \] where \(SD\) is the sample standard deviation and \(n\) is the number of observations used to compute the mean and SD for a given subgroup. Finally, calculate the minimum and maximum values of the error bars by taking the mean and subtracting/adding the SE.

summary_dat <- BianLeslieCimpian %>%  # change this to your cleaned up data 
 group_by(study, trait, gender, age) %>%
  summarise(
    M = mean(stereo),
    SD = sd(stereo),
    n = n()
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    SE = SD / sqrt(n),   
    y_min = M - SE,
    y_max = M + SE
  ) %>% mutate(gender = recode(gender, "1" = "male", "2"= "female")) %>% mutate(trait = recode(trait, "0" = "nice", "1"= "smart"))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'study', 'trait', 'gender' (override with `.groups` argument)
summary_dat %>%
ggplot(aes(x = age, y = M)) + 
geom_point(aes(color = gender)) + 
  geom_line(aes(color = gender)) + 
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = y_min, ymax = y_max), width = 0.1) + 
  facet_grid(trait ~ study, labeller = "label_both") + # use face grid to split by trait and study
  scale_color_brewer(type = "qual", palette = 6, direction = -1) + 
  labs(x = "Age (years)", y = "Own Gender Trait Mean Scores", color = "Gender") + 
  ylim(0, 1) + # add limits
  theme_minimal()

2 Emerging adulthood

The goal of the study was to investigate correlations between measures of emerging adulthood and a range of other psychological constructs, including subjective well-being, mindfulness, belonging, self-efficacy, somatic health, and perceived stress, among others. Data were collected by collaborators from 32 different academic institutions. You can view the survey instrument here: https://osf.io/t3w2p/

2.1 Data cleaning (3 pts)

Create a clean version of the dataset, stored in an object called adulthood_clean, after doing the following:

  1. Exclude respondents who completed less than 80% of the survey (the variable progress reports the percentage of the survey instrument completed).
  2. Exclude respondents who failed the attention check (attention == 7 corresponds to passing the attention check; missing values or values less than 7 correspond to failing the attention check).
  3. Exclude respondents who completed the survey in less than 10 minutes (the duration variable reports completion time in seconds).
  4. Create a composite self-efficacy measure (call it self_efficacy) equal to the sum of efficacy_1 through efficacy_10.
  5. Create a composite sense of belonging measure (call it belonging) equal to the sum of belong_1 through belong_10.
  6. Create a composite measure of adult achievements (call it adulthood) equal to the sum of moa1#2_1 through moa1#2_10 and moa2#2_1 through moa2#2_10.
adulthood_clean <- adulthood_dat%>% filter (progress >= 80, attention == 7, duration >= 600) %>% mutate(
    self_efficacy = rowSums(select(., starts_with("efficacy"))),
    belonging = rowSums(select(., starts_with("belong"))),
    adulthood = rowSums(select(., starts_with("moa")))
  )
